history.content: You just need to self-study op-amp and you should be fine. I'd suggest you find a friend who had taken EE16A to be your lab partner.

In terms of workload and in terms of concept difficulty, how huge of a jump would this be if I only self study EE16A (so no hands-on lab experience)?

Other workload: CS61B, Math 53(have prior multivariable calculus experience), seminar/decal.

I was pretty solid with concepts of circuits from AP Physics C: E&M from HS (+lab), and while I have the mathematical intuition to perform calculations relating to circuits quickly, I need to work harder to apply what I've learned conceptually to building actual circuits in a lab based setting.
